# axion_em_gr

`axion_em_gr` is a modular Python framework for exploratory numerical studies of axion electrodynamics in fixed 3+1 curved spacetimes.

The code evolves an axion-like scalar field coupled to electromagnetic fields using a 3+1 formulation. It supports flat-space, weak gravitational-wave backgrounds, compact-object-inspired metrics, prescribed rotating magnetic dipoles, curved two-dimensional operators, constraint diagnostics, electric constraint cleaning, parameter sweeps and scientific visualization.

The package is intended as a research and prototyping tool for reduced models of axion electrodynamics around compact objects, gravitational-wave backgrounds and magnetized astrophysical environments.

---

## Main features

- Modular 1D and 2D finite-difference grids.
- Explicit RK4 time integration.
- Axion field evolution with configurable potential.
- Maxwell evolution with axion coupling.
- Fixed 3+1 background geometries.
- Flat spacetime, TT gravitational-wave backgrounds and compact-object toy metrics.
- Isotropic Schwarzschild-inspired metrics.
- Prescribed rotating magnetic dipole backgrounds.
- Covariant 2D scalar Laplacian, divergence and Maxwell curl operators.
- Electric and magnetic constraint diagnostics.
- Flat and curved electric constraint cleaning.
- YAML-based configuration system.
- Parameter sweeps.
- Diagnostic plots and scientific animations.

---

## Physical system

The evolved axion variables are

$$a(t,x^i), \qquad \Pi(t,x^i).$$

The electromagnetic variables are the Eulerian electric and magnetic fields

$$E^i(t,x^j), \qquad B^i(t,x^j).$$

The axion sector is evolved according to

$$\partial_t a = N\Pi+\beta^i\partial_i a,$$

$$\partial_t\Pi = \beta^i\partial_i\Pi + N \left[ D_iD^i a + K\Pi - D_i(\ln N)D^i a - \frac{dV}{da} - g_{a\gamma}E_iB^i \right].$$

The electromagnetic constraints are

$$D_iB^i=0,$$

$$D_iE^i = \rho - g_{a\gamma}B^iD_i a.$$

The Maxwell evolution equations are

$$\partial_t B^i = \mathcal{L}_\beta B^i + NK B^i - \epsilon^{ijk}D_j(NE_k),$$

$$\partial_t E^i = \mathcal{L}_\beta E^i + NK E^i - \epsilon^{ijk}D_j(NB_k) + Nj^i + g_{a\gamma}N\epsilon^{ijk}E_kD_ja - g_{a\gamma}N\Pi B^i.$$

The default potential is

$$V(a)=\frac{1}{2}m_a^2a^2,$$

but other potentials can be added through the potential interface.

---

## Current scope

The current version supports fixed-background simulations. It does not evolve the Einstein equations.

Implemented levels of physical modelling include:

- flat-space axion and Maxwell tests,
- axion-Maxwell coupling in 1D and 2D,
- weak gravitational-wave background examples,
- axion halos/clouds interacting with electromagnetic backgrounds,
- prescribed rotating magnetic dipoles,
- compact-object-inspired fixed metrics,
- curved 2D axion and Maxwell operators,
- curved electric constraint cleaning.

The rotating dipole and compact-object cases are reduced models. They are not yet full plasma, force-free, magnetohydrodynamic or dynamical-spacetime simulations.

---

